Machine Learning & Predictive Analytics¶

Final Project: Classifying Cars Using Deep Learning¶

May 27, 2023¶

The Cars dataset contains 16,185 images of 196 classes of cars. The data is split into 8,144 training images and 8,041 testing images, where each class has been split roughly in a 50-50 split. Classes are typically at the level of Make, Model, Year, ex. 2012 Tesla Model S or 2012 BMW M3 coupe.

The data has been downloaded locally and is stored in train/test folders with folders containing images of the specific cars

Specify Parameters¶

In [10]:
# Ensures images will be square in shape
img_width, img_height = 224, 224

# Number of images in the Train set
nb_train_samples = 8144 

# Number of images in the Test set
nb_validation_samples = 8041

# Other Parameters for a base model. Later I perform a Grid Search.
epochs = 20     # Number of complete iterations through the training set
batch_size = 32 # Number of data points that are processed during training
n_classes = 196 # Number of distinct car classes we will classify

Data Pre-Processing & Augmentation¶

In [11]:
train_data_dir = path_base + '/car_data/train'
validation_data_dir = path_base + '/car_data/test'

train_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(
    rescale=1./255,          # Normalize the pixel values between 0 and 1
    shear_range=0.2,         # Tilts the image by a maximum radian amount
    zoom_range=0.2,          # Zooms in/out by a maximum factor
    fill_mode = 'constant',  # Method to fill empty pixels resulting from transformations
    cval = 1,                # Constant value - in this case, White
    rotation_range = 5,      # Rotates the image by a maximum +/- degree
    width_shift_range=0.2,   # Maximum horizontal shift in either direction
    height_shift_range=0.2,  # Maximum vertical shift in either direction
    horizontal_flip=True)    # Allows random horizontal flipping

# For the Test data, we will only rescale it
test_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1./255)

train_generator = train_datagen.flow_from_directory(
    train_data_dir,
    target_size=(img_width, img_height),
    batch_size=batch_size,
    class_mode='categorical')

validation_generator = test_datagen.flow_from_directory(
    validation_data_dir,
    target_size=(img_width, img_height),
    batch_size=batch_size,
    class_mode='categorical')

Model 1: ResNet50¶

This first iteration of the model uses ResNet50 which is a pretrained model that has starting weights. I add in some final layers including the output softmax layer.

Softmax is used to select the class with the highest probability in terms of classifying the car as the final result. It does this by transforming the previous layer output into a probability distribution over the classes (ensures the predicted class probabilities sum to 1).

In [26]:
# Clear previous session (release GPU memory resources by resetting backend state)
k.clear_session()

# Load in ResNet50
ResNet50, preprocess_input = Classifiers.get('resnet50')
In [27]:
# Create the base model
base_model = ResNet50(input_shape=(img_width, img_height, 3),
                      weights='imagenet', # Use imagenet weights
                      include_top=False)  # Ignore the top layer so we can add our own
In [28]:
# Extract the output from the base model we created
x = base_model.output 

# Add a Pooling Layer to flatten the output of ResNet into 1-D tensor
x = keras.layers.GlobalAveragePooling2D()(x)

# Use Softmax to perform the final layer classification
predictions = Dense(units=train_generator.num_classes, 
                    activation= 'softmax')(x)

# Establish the new model with the outputs and base model
model = Model(inputs = base_model.input, 
              outputs = predictions)

# Compile the model
model.compile(optimizer = 'adam', 
              loss='categorical_crossentropy', 
              metrics=['acc'])

# Show summary
model.summary()

In [19]:
# Extract the output from the base model we created
x = base_model.output 

x = Dense(1000, kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l1_l2(0.01), 
                activity_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.01))(x)

x = Activation('relu')(x)

# Add a Dropout layer to prevent overfitting
#x = Dropout(0.2)(x)

x = Dense(500, kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l1_l2(0.01), activity_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.01))(x)

x = Activation('relu')(x)

# Add a Pooling Layer to flatten the output of ResNet into 1-D tensor
x = keras.layers.GlobalAveragePooling2D()(x)

# Use Softmax to perform the final layer classification
predictions = Dense(units=train_generator.num_classes, 
                    activation= 'softmax')(x)

# Establish the new model with the outputs and base model
model = Model(inputs = base_model.input, 
              outputs = predictions)

# Compile the model
model.compile(optimizer = 'sgd', 
              loss='categorical_crossentropy', 
              metrics=['acc'])

# Show summary
model.summary()

Model 3: ResNet50 - with adjustments¶

In [69]:
# Create the base model
base_model = ResNet50(input_shape=(img_width, img_height, 3),
                      weights='imagenet', # Use imagenet weights
                      include_top=False)  # Ignore the top layer so we can add our own
In [70]:
# Extract the output from the base model we created
x = base_model.output 

# Add a Dropout layer to prevent overfitting
x = Dropout(0.30)(x)

# Add a flattening layer but preserve spatial features 
x = Flatten()(x)

# Use Softmax to perform the final layer classification
predictions = Dense(units=train_generator.num_classes, 
                    activation= 'softmax')(x)

# Establish the new model with the outputs and base model
model = Model(inputs = base_model.input, 
              outputs = predictions)

# Compile the model
model.compile(optimizer = 'adam', 
              loss = 'categorical_crossentropy', 
              metrics = ['acc'])

# Show summary
model.summary()
